    <item>
      <title>Introduction</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc410/iii-web/19-serialization/01-introduction/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc410/iii-web/19-serialization/01-introduction/index.html</guid>
      <description>Earlier in this course, we learned that an object-oriented program can be thought of as two different parts, the state of the program, and the behavior in the program. In this chapter, we&amp;rsquo;re going to discuss ways that we can save the program&amp;rsquo;s state while it is running. By doing so, we can then resume the program at a later time by simply loading that state back into memory.
This is a process generally known as serialization, though other languages may use other terms.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>State Review</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc410/iii-web/19-serialization/02-state-review/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc410/iii-web/19-serialization/02-state-review/index.html</guid>
      <description>First, let&amp;rsquo;s quickly review the state of a program. Recall from an earlier chapter that the state of a program consists of all of the variables and objects stored in memory. So, any time we create a new variable or instantiate a new object in our code, that adds to the overall state of the program.
1
In the diagram above, we can visualize an object in object-oriented programming as the state, with a set of variables in the center, and the behaviors around those variables defining how we can use, interact with, and modify that state.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Text Formats</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc410/iii-web/19-serialization/03-test-formats/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc410/iii-web/19-serialization/03-test-formats/index.html</guid>
      <description>YouTube Video
Video Materials
So, now that we understand state, let&amp;rsquo;s talk about how we can serialize it in a way that is easy to parse and understand. There are really two major options we can choose from: a textual representation of the data, and a binary representation. Let&amp;rsquo;s look at text formats first.
Text Data Formats There are many different ways that we can serialize data into a textual format.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Binary Formats</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc410/iii-web/19-serialization/04-binary-formats/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc410/iii-web/19-serialization/04-binary-formats/index.html</guid>
      <description>We already know that all the data stored by a computer is in a binary format. So, it of course makes sense to also look at ways we can store a program&amp;rsquo;s state using a binary file format.
Binary Files Many programming languages, including Java and Python, include libraries that can be used to generate binary files containing the state of an object in memory. Each language, and indeed each version of the language, may use a different format for storing the binary data in the file.</description>
    </item>
