    <item>
      <title>Items to Exclude</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc410/iii-web/19-serialization/07-exclude/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc410/iii-web/19-serialization/07-exclude/index.html</guid>
      <description>Another important concept to keep in mind when serializing data is that there are some items that don&amp;rsquo;t serialize very well, and others that can be omitted. Let&amp;rsquo;s review a few of those now.
Operating System Objects One example of things that don&amp;rsquo;t serialize well are objects provided by the operating system itself. This includes things such as open files, input and output streams, and threads. In each case, these objects rely on data provided by the operating system, making it difficult to serialize the object directly.</description>
